Overview
This module focused on building practical skills in Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) platforms, specifically Splunk and the ELK Stack. 
The goal was to move beyond surface-level familiarity and develop the ability to write meaningful queries, build dashboards, 
and investigate simulated alerts in a realistic environment.

Key Concepts Covered
Splunk

Writing SPL (Search Processing Language) queries to filter and correlate log data
Building dashboards to visualize alert trends and event timelines
Creating alerts based on threshold conditions and behavioral anomalies
Investigating simulated security events from raw log data

ELK Stack (Elasticsearch, Logstash, Kibana)

Understanding log ingestion pipelines through Logstash
Querying indexed data in Elasticsearch using KQL
Visualizing security data in Kibana dashboards
Correlating events across multiple log sources


Skills Demonstrated

Translating a security question into a SIEM query
Filtering high-volume log data to isolate relevant events
Identifying patterns indicative of malicious activity
Documenting findings in a structured format for escalation


Key Takeaways
Working with SIEM platforms reinforced that effective alert investigation is less about the tool and more about asking the right questions. Starting broad and narrowing down — filtering by time window, source IP, user account, or event ID — is the core workflow regardless of which platform you are using.
Tuning alerts to reduce false positives is equally important as writing detection rules. An alert that fires constantly loses its value quickly in a real SOC environment.
